column4: Jessica L. Kelly a, James R. Hagler b, Ian Kaplan
column6: Semiochemical lures reduce emigration and enhance pest control services in open-field predator augmentation
column53: This study has four treatments: 1 predator release + Predator pheromone, 2 predator release + MeSa, Predator release alone, and 4 no predator release + no semiochemical. There is no difference in Podisus attraction between the semiochemicals and one of the controls (3). The only attraction effect is on tachinidae and parasitoid hymenoptera, which are not the targeted natural enemies. I am reporting those natural enemies

column4: Maeda, T; Kishimoto, H; Wright, LC; James, DG
column6: Mixture of Synthetic Herbivore-induced Plant Volatiles Attracts More Stethorus punctum picipes (Casey) (Coleoptera: Coccinellidae) than a Single Volatile
column53: This Paper evaluates 3 HIPVS: MeSA, cis-3-henene-1-ol, and cis-3-hexenyl acetate, as well as the mixture of the three volatiles and a control to attract a ladybug species. Their large-scale field experiment was only significant during the second evaluation when the mix of volatiles attracted more individuals. Other than that, there is no significant evidence that using these volatiles or their mixture effectively attracts ladybugs. I would also exclude it.
